</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Use Greenhouse Patch Tape</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Season-long repairs</strong></li>
    <li><strong>High sun exposure</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Important structural areas</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This is the better choice when reliability matters.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Clear Tarp Tape Makes Sense</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Emergency repairs</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Short-term use</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Low-stress areas</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It works best as a temporary solution rather than a permanent fix.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Using Tarp Tape for Long-Term Repairs</h3>
  <p>
    It often degrades quickly under UV exposure.
  </p>

  <h3>Poor Surface Preparation</h3>
  <p>
    Dirt and moisture reduce adhesion for both types.
  </p>

  <h3>Not Reinforcing Larger Tears</h3>
  <p>
    Big damage areas may need support beyond tape alone.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Apply Repair Tape Properly</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Clean and dry the damaged area.</li>
    <li>Apply tape smoothly without wrinkles.</li>
    <li>Press firmly to ensure full contact.</li>
    <li>Apply tape on both sides for stronger repairs if possible.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Good application improves performance regardless of tape type.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into Greenhouse Maintenance</h2>

  <p>
    Repair tape is part of regular greenhouse upkeep. Quick repairs prevent small tears from becoming larger problems.
  </p>

